Data Acquisition and Plotting tests

Data Download

q <- readNWISdv(siteNumbers = '06752260',
                parameterCd = '00060',
                startDate = '2017-01-01',
                endDate = '2022-01-01') %>%
  rename(q = 'X_00060_00003')

Static Data Plotter

ggplot(q, aes(x = Date, y = q)) + 
  geom_line() + 
  ylab('Q (cfs)') + 
  ggtitle('Discharge in the Poudre River, Fort Collins')

Interactive Data Plotter

q_xts <- xts(q$q, order.by = q$Date)


dygraph(q_xts) %>%
  dyAxis("y", label = "Discharge (cfs)")

Poudre Paragraph

The Poudre River runs from the Continental Divide to the east, down into the city of Fort Collins. In the city, it flows year round. It is a popular area for recreation, such as rafting, kayaking, fishing, tubing, and more. The river is dominated by snow melt, and therefore has a strong peak in the spring or early summer and relatively low flows in the winter.
